[Botulinum type C toxin has been incriminated in almost all instances of
intoxication in minks and foxes; storage of meat by-products in metal
drums, in which anaerobic conditions prevail, provides excellent conditions
for production of the toxin. The reported absence of the incriminated C
toxin in the various feed components may indicate that the contamination
occurred incidentally after the mixing or manufacture of the final toxic
batch. Birds, in which toxicoinfection by Botulinum type C is not uncommon,
are plausible candidates. - Mod.AS]
[The proposed mechanism may well be as moderator AS has suggested in his
comments above, but there are several additional questions that come to
mind -- food for thought. The individual ingredients were tested, but was
the final feed tested? Did the mixer have any foreign material in
it? Was the feed mixer cleaned well? The fact that the foxes died on 30
to 40 different farms tends to go against the theory of contamination
having occurred at the feeding site. Was there any additive sprayed on the
food? Often times digest and flavoring are added to canine or carnivore
food. Was this tested for _Clostridium botulinum_ spores and toxin? - Mod.TG]
